  protein: 35 g
---

First off, boil @water{250%ml} for your couscous. Cut the very tops and bottoms from your @green beans{100}(top and tailed) and then cut each @British chicken thighs{3} into equal sized strips. Lastly, chop up your @dried apricots{3} into tiny pieces.

Next up, zest a ¼ of a tsp of @lemon zest{¼%tsp} and squeeze out the juice of @lemon{½}(juiced) into a #bowl{}.
> When you zest the lemon use a fine grater (or preferably a 'zester') and don't zest down to the bitter white part.
> To juice the lemon simply cut it in half, stick a fork inside and squeeze.

Put your @couscous{½%cup} in a bowl and pour in the 250ml of boiling water together with half the @chicken stock{1}, half the lemon juice, half the lemon zest and @salt{¼%tsp}. Cover the bowl immediately with a #lid{} (or some #clingfilm{}) and leave it to soak for at least ~{10%minutes}.

Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a #nonstick pan{} on medium heat. Cook the chicken thighs with a @salt{pinch} for around ~{4%minutes}, until they're browned off. Next, add the @honey{1%tbsp} for a minute. If you only have a small pan, cook in batches rather than overcrowding it.

Add in the @ground cinnamon{½%tsp}, @cumin{½%tsp}, @organic tomatoes{1%can}(tinned), @?sugar{½%tsp}, the remaining stock pot and the remaining lemon zest and juice. Give everything a stir and then add in the beans and apricots. Cook, uncovered, on medium heat for about ~{8%minutes} or until the beans are tender.

> If you don't want the recipe to be too sweet, leave out the sugar. The apricots will already give a hint of sweetness to it.

Briefly consider taking part in a camel race.

To serve, simply fluff up your couscous with a #fork{} and top it with your chicken mix. Yalla!